            <p class="about-paragraph">
                What I've built here is more than just a <strong>“shopping list”</strong> 
            app. It's a clean demonstration of how a full-stack Express 
            application is structured and how responsibilities are 
            separated across the system. On the backend, I've 
            organized routes using an Express router, kept data access 
            abstracted through modules like fakeDb and my JSONL-based 
            log reader, and handled asynchronous operations with 
            async/await. On the frontend, I'm using EJS as a 
            templating engine to dynamically render content, including 
            partials for layout reuse (nav, content, footer), which 
            mirrors how larger production apps manage views. Even small 
            decisions, like passing a file variable to control which partial 
            renders, show an understanding of scalable layout patterns 
            rather than hardcoding pages.
            </p>

            <p class="about-paragraph">
                I'm also touching on important real-world concepts that go 
            beyond just rendering data. The use of a .jsonl file introduces 
            a lightweight logging mechanism, which is exactly the kind of 
            pattern used in production systems for tracking events and 
            debugging behavior. Structuring my app this way makes it 
            testable: routes can be exercised independently, data modules 
            can be mocked or swapped, and tools like Jest and Supertest can 
            validate both logic and HTTP responses. Altogether, this app 
            demonstrates core software engineering principles: modularity, 
            separation of concerns, and predictable data flow.
            </p>
